  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The system has optimized morphology within a static fitness landscape. All organisms are converging to the same high-fitness form because there's no pressure to be different—the environment is uniform and unchanging. Evolution has found the global optimum *for that structure* and has nowhere to go. Breaking the plateau requires either (a) introducing new dimensions organisms haven't optimized (behavior, energetics), or (b) making the fitness landscape itself dynamic (ecology, arms races). Parameter tuning within the current structure will never escape this local maximum.; [medium] Introduce energy budgets and active metabolism. Organisms consume energy to move, grow, and reproduce. Death occurs when energy hits zero. Shift from static morphology + beauty evaluation to dynamic survival + foraging behavior. — Current system likely has organisms converging to a static morphology that scores well. Energy budgets create moment-to-moment pressure: organisms must *behave* to survive, not just *exist*. This opens behavioral evolution (how to forage, when to reproduce) as an orthogonal dimension to morphology. Beauty can be redefined to reward efficiency-of-motion, creating coupling between aesthetic and survival metrics.; [medium] Add sensory-motor coupling: organisms can sense local chemical/energy gradients and respond in real-time (chemotaxis, phototaxis, avoidance). Decision logic becomes: sense → decide → act, rather than static genetically-encoded behavior. Beauty scored on grace-of-movement and trajectory patterns. — Beauty is currently evaluated on static form. Introducing dynamic behavior and *reactive intelligence* creates new degrees of freedom. Organisms can now be evaluated on movement elegance, efficiency of navigation, behavioral symmetry. This breaks the local optimum because the fitness landscape is no longer frozen—it evolves as organisms learn to sense and respond.; [hard] Introduce ecological relationships: predator-prey dynamics or resource competition. Organisms compete for limited resources; some organisms can consume others. Create an arms race where no single morphology/strategy dominates indefinitely. — Plateaus occur when selection pressure vanishes. A monoculture has found the peak and stops. Predator-prey or competition creates *frequency-dependent selection*: the best strategy changes as the population changes. This prevents convergence and forces continuous adaptation. Beauty can reward both predator elegance (hunting grace) and prey elegance (escape artistry).",
